First, we need to find the symmetric difference between sets A and B (A Δ B). The symmetric difference between two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection.

A = {1, 2, 3, 4}
B = {2, 3, 4}

Intersection of A and B (A ∩ B) = {2, 3, 4}

Now, we find the symmetric difference (A Δ B):

Elements in A but not in B: {1}
Elements in B but not in A: {}
A Δ B = {1}

Now, we need to find the symmetric difference between the set (A Δ B) and C:

(A Δ B) = {1}
C = {3, 4, 5, 6}

Intersection of (A Δ B) and C ((A Δ B) ∩ C) = {}

Now, we find the symmetric difference ((A Δ B) Δ C):

Elements in (A Δ B) but not in C: {1}
Elements in C but not in (A Δ B): {3, 4, 5, 6}
(A Δ B) Δ C = {1, 3, 4, 5, 6}
